Fortunately, another insight from the Women’s Economic Empowerment Project has shown that women in the intervention arm are using their increased income to invest in children’s education (Thompson & Smith-Nielsen 2016). This in turn could imply that fewer women would have to resort to carrying out abortions, or terminations through miscarriage in the future as a result of poorer socioeconomic conditions. As a consequence this could be considered in the future a way to deal with unplanned pregnancies. For other types of interventions this type of outcome (“secondary benefit”) would seem to be an opportunity.
On the negative side the anti-abortion community say the following:
Unlicensed and unregulated abortion services place women at risk
One day they could be using oral methotrexate to end their own pregnancies.
Others could be using other drugs, injecting their arms after cleaning out a medicine cabinet, or trying any number of other unsafe methods. Their last resort may be to have an abortion in a humanitarian centre, a highly skilled, legal and appropriately managed environment.
Few people wan to see more women forced to horrifically unsafe abortion techniques.
We need to make sure that such a future never comes.
A 1998 decision to introduce abortion to ALMAS, a group of humanitarian centres in northern Burkina Faso.
